## Stems

The stem is the main structural part of a word to which an affix is attached. It expresses the lexical meaning of the word, which is modified through affixation [1:33].
Stems can be either primary (non-derived) or derived:
- Primary stems are those in which no active, commonly used affixes in the modern language can be identified.

- Derived bases are those formed from primary stem using active affixes. A derived stem can have a sequence of affixes. The meaning of such a multi-morphemic word is synthesized from the meaning of the primary stem and all of its affixes.


## Lexical roots

Primary stems represent the root of the word in the modern language. They are regarded by the morphological analyzer as irreducible and not subject to further analysis.

Although some lexical roots may be decomposable through comparative or historical analysis, their constituent elements have lost their independent meaning and usage in the modern language and are considered no longer productive [1:33-34].

Lexical roots are listed in the lexicon with a label indicating the type of primary stem, such as nominal, verbal, and other features. The type of stem with affixes can be attached and can trigger phonographemic changes.

A lexical root to be included in the lexicon must follow these two main principles:
- It must not contain productive affixes.
- It must be used as an independent word in modern Yakut.

In the word *кыһын* (winter), the dead affix *-ын* can be identified, which has been preserved only in a few words. The root кыс has already become an archaism [1:34].

Exceptions to the first rule may include lexicalized modals and conjunctions, when this status is indicated in the source grammar.

