## Affixes

An affix is called the simplest morphological element (morpheme) attached to the stemp. Affixes are not used separately from the word stem.
Yakut affixes can be monosyllabic or disyllabic. They can also consist of a single vowel or a single consonant [1:34].

Affixes are conventionally divided into derivational and inflectional. In Ubryatova the following principle is given [1:35]:

- derivational: affixes that complement or change the lexical meaning of the stem and form a derived stem from it, which acts as a new independent word capable of taking various affixes.

- inflectional affixes: do not change the lexical meaning of the stem. They are used only to express the relationship or connection of a given word to other words within a sentence.

