## Part-of-speech

The question of the principles of identifying and classifying parts of speech is one of the complex and difficult questions of grammar, causing disputes and disagreements among linguists [1:36].
However, in practice, different languages continue to use mainly the traditional scheme of parts of speech, which has taken root in Indo-European languages since the times of Ancient Greece and Rome. Thus, disputes relate mainly to the area of theoretical interpretation and some individual details of classification. In the Turkic languages, they also mainly use the traditional scheme with partial changes and additions in relation to the features of individual languages. The same was observed in the history of the study of the Yakut language.

In the classification of parts of speech, it is customary to compare and combine words and their categories into separate groups according to their most common features [1:37].
In this regard, words in a language are primarily divided into full-fledged and functional words [1:37].

- The first type includes those words that have a specific real meaning reflecting reality.
- The type of function words includes those words that do not have an independent material meaning reflecting reality, but express only relationships and connections between full-meaning words.

In speech, they cannot play the role of a separate independent unit and are used only together with some full-meaning word, complementing or clarifying its meaning

In the Yakut language, words and lexical and grammatical categories of words (parts of speech) can also be compared and grouped according to their relation to inflection forms. In this regard, all words of the Yakut language can be conditionally divided into the following three large groups: 1) words of the nominal type (declension), 2) words of the verb type (conjugated), and 3) unchangeable words. Such a division (like any other grouping of linguistic phenomena of a similar type) is, of course, only conditional and very approximate. However, inflection forms in the Yakut language, especially for significant words, seem to be a fairly stable and characteristic grammatical feature that can have a preferential meaning in the classification of parts of speech.

The role of a word in a sentence, its connection with certain grammatical categories or concepts, as well as the nature of its grammatical changes, largely depend on the nature of its basic lexical meaning. For example, the category and forms of tense are inherent only to those words that express the concept of an action or state, and case to words expressing the concept of an object [1:36].



In grammars of agglutinative languages, postpositions are usually called function words that correspond to prepositions of Indo-European languages. These words are usually treated as a special part of speech. However, in grammars of Turkic languages, it has not yet been possible to clearly and convincingly implement such an understanding of these words [2:73].





