### Particles

Particles are unchangeable words that do not have a completely independent lexical meaning and serve to supplement or modify the meaning of other words or entire groups of words [2:73].

One should distinguish particles from service words and auxiliary verbs, which are similar in function. They differ from particles in the following ways [2:79]:

1. Particles are immutable words, while service words can be declined, and auxiliary verbs can be conjugated.
2. Particles do not have an independent lexical meaning and cannot be used separately, whereas service words and auxiliary verbs, in addition to their service function, can also function as independent words.

### Conjunctions

Conjunctions: unchangeable words expressing connections and relationships between words, phrases and sentences.
There are very few proper conjunctions in the Yakut language. Subordinating conjunctions are not developed at all and their functions are served by participial and adverbial participial phrases [2].
Words used in the meaning of conjunctions can be divided into three groups [2]:
- proper conjunctions;
- simple words used as conjunctions;
- compound words and word combinations in the function of conjunctions.

The first group include unchangeable words that are mainly used as conjunctions. These words are listed in the lexicon.
The second group includes, first of all, a number of particles that appear in the meaning of conjunctions, but also some adverbs, pronouns and numerals. These words are listed as their respective types.

